HOW TO USE THIS DRIVE
---------------------

1. Install Kiwix for your platform:
   - Look in the kiwix/ directory on this drive
   - Choose the right version for your system:
     kiwix/linux/     - Linux (AppImage, just run it)
     kiwix/windows/   - Windows
     kiwix/macos/     - macOS
     kiwix/android/   - Android (APK)
     kiwix/serve/     - Server / Raspberry Pi (kiwix-serve)

2. Open any .zim file from the zim/ directory using Kiwix.
   Start with Wikipedia — it's the single most valuable file here.

3. Everything works completely offline. No internet needed.

WHAT'S ON THIS DRIVE
--------------------

zim/     - Compressed knowledge archives (readable with Kiwix)
           Wikipedia, medical references, repair guides, textbooks,
           programming courses, dictionaries, primary sources, and more.

pdfs/    - Curated PDF collection: survival manuals, field medicine,
           agriculture, construction, food preservation.

kiwix/   - Kiwix reader software for all platforms.

maps/    - Offline maps (if included in this loadout).

SERVING ON A NETWORK
--------------------

To make this library available to everyone on your local network:

    # Using the bundled kiwix-serve:
    cd kiwix/serve/
    ./kiwix-serve --port 8080 ../../zim/*.zim

    # Or with Docker:
    docker run -v /path/to/zim:/data -p 8080:80 kiwix/kiwix-serve '*.zim'

Then open http://localhost:8080 in any browser on your network.

A Raspberry Pi + this drive + a WiFi access point = an instant offline
knowledge hotspot.

ABOUT
-----

Built with "The Ark" — https://github.com/xram/the-ark
Powered by Kiwix (https://kiwix.org), the open-source offline reader.

The ZIM format is the standard for offline knowledge archiving, used by
NGOs, deployed in schools without internet across Africa, and smuggled
into countries where information is restricted.

You don't need the internet to read any of this. That's the whole point.

Good luck.
